10:16.700 --> 10:21.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Remember, the subsidies are
less than the subsidies that
the Obamacare proposal gives,

10:22.866 --> 10:26.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and they go to a much,
much smaller level.

10:26.733 --> 10:28.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The insurance they
cover is much less.

10:28.733 --> 10:31.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It is not comparable.

10:31.100 --> 10:35.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You can't cut $770
billion and say, oh,
it's not going to affect
anything; 22 million people

10:37.166 --> 10:39.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are going to lose coverage
because of this bill.

10:39.133 --> 10:41.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Avik Roy,
how do you answer that?

10:41.100 --> 10:45.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AVIK ROY: Yes, so the CBO
estimate, this 22 million number
that Zeke is talking about

10:45.966 --> 10:50.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is largely driven by erroneous
aspects of the Congressional
Budget Office's methodology.

10:50.433 --> 10:55.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The CBO believes that 15 million
people will drop out of the
insurance market in 2018 because

10:57.500 --> 11:02.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they will no longer face a fine
for not purchasing coverage, the
individual mandate that we all

11:02.166 --> 11:04.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
hear so much about.

11:04.200 --> 11:08.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, ultimately, about 18
million of that 22 million is
driven by the lack of a fine

11:10.033 --> 11:11.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
forcing people to have
coverage, so it's not
driven by a lack of funding.

11:11.733 --> 11:12.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
There's robust funding.

11:12.866 --> 11:13.866 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

11:13.866 --> 11:15.566 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

11:15.566 --> 11:16.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
EZEKIEL EMANUEL: If you
don't like the message,
attack the messenger.

11:16.233 --> 11:18.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

11:18.300 --> 11:20.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AVIK ROY: No, but this is
a fundamental problem with
the CBO's methodology.

11:20.366 --> 11:23.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's the reason why
Obamacare has an individual
mandate in the first place.

11:23.200 --> 11:27.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Senator Obama in 2008, he
opposed having an individual
mandate in his bill.

11:27.166 --> 11:31.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it was only included because
the CBO told him that 16 million
-- the coverage, the statistic

11:31.866 --> 11:34.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of coverage would
be affected by that.

11:34.400 --> 11:36.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right,
I don't want to spend
the whole time on the
CBO, the Congressional

11:36.333 --> 11:38.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Budget Office, but just
a quick response to that.

11:38.700 --> 11:40.733 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

11:40.733 --> 11:42.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
EZEKIEL EMANUEL: Well, again,
I think he's attacking the
messenger because he doesn't

11:42.033 --> 11:43.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
like the message.

11:43.600 --> 11:47.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the fact is that the CBO
is the independent arbiter.

11:47.500 --> 11:49.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Their methods aren't universal.

11:49.333 --> 11:52.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They don't get it
necessarily exactly right.

11:52.033 --> 11:57.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But you're not going to go
from 22 million uninsured down
to a more tolerable number.

11:59.066 --> 12:02.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It seems unconscionable that
senators could vote to throw 22
million people off of insurance.

12:04.366 --> 12:08.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And now we have the irony that
John McCain is delaying the
vote, a guy who needed surgery

12:09.266 --> 12:12.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that cost $30,000.

12:12.000 --> 12:14.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He certainly couldn't afford
it just out of nowhere.

12:14.966 --> 12:16.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Insurance has to pay.

12:16.600 --> 12:18.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And we're going to
get 22 million people
with less insurance.

12:18.733 --> 12:23.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Another aspect
of this, Avik Roy, is this --
in an effort to make insurance

12:25.333 --> 12:28.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
more affordable, what we
now see is a Senate bill
offering alternatives
that lower premiums,

12:30.433 --> 12:34.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but they do this by cutting
back on the amount of
coverage, on what is covered.

12:36.100 --> 12:39.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're creating -- the criticism
here is that you're creating
two markets, one for people

12:39.566 --> 12:44.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who can afford to continue to
get good medical care and those
who would be left out because

12:45.333 --> 12:46.566 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they can't.

12:46.566 --> 12:49.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
How do you defend this
part of the legislation?

12:49.466 --> 12:54.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AVIK ROY: Well, Judy, I would
use -- I would challenge the
accuracy of the description

12:55.666 --> 12:57.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that you just gave
of the measure.

12:57.800 --> 12:59.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think we're talking about
the Ted Cruz amendment to
the Senate health care bill.

12:59.900 --> 13:04.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what that amendment is
trying to do is say, OK, sick
people are going to have much

13:06.066 --> 13:08.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more expensive coverage because
they consume more health care.

13:08.700 --> 13:13.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, let's have direct taxpayer
subsidies in this regulated
market to ensure that they

13:13.300 --> 13:15.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
can find affordable coverage.

13:15.333 --> 13:19.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the fact, Judy, is that
tens of millions of Americans
who can't afford coverage can't

13:19.666 --> 13:23.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
afford that coverage not because
they're sick, but because
they're healthy and insurance

13:23.333 --> 13:25.366 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
costs too much.

13:25.366 --> 13:28.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Obamacare over the last
four years has doubled or
tripled their premiums.

13:28.400 --> 13:33.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HHS, Health and Human Services,
researchers have estimated
that premiums have increased

13:33.133 --> 13:35.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for that population by
at least 100 percent
over the last four years.

13:35.666 --> 13:39.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, what Ted Cruz is
trying to do is say
let's make sure there's
coverage that is affordable

13:39.533 --> 13:42.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for healthy people, as
well as for sick people.

13:42.233 --> 13:46.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you do that by having a
market that really is focused on
covering people who are already

13:46.500 --> 13:50.966 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sick, which requires a
different kind of insurance,
and people who are
healthy and who need lower

13:50.966 --> 13:51.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
premiums as a result.

13:51.966 --> 13:53.200 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

13:53.200 --> 13:55.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
EZEKIEL EMANUEL: Let's
make three quick points.

13:55.500 --> 14:00.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
First of all, the subsidies that
the Republicans are going to
give are going to be much less

14:00.100 --> 14:05.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and smaller, driving up
what people have to pay, and
especially their deductible.

14:06.633 --> 14:10.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They don't do anything
about affordability
in this bill at all.

14:12.200 --> 14:15.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They don't change the
long-term trajectory of
health care costs one bit.

14:17.800 --> 14:21.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Second of all, the fact is
that every medical organization
has come out against this bill

14:22.533 --> 14:24.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and says it's going to
be bad for patients.

14:24.500 --> 14:29.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the health insurance
industry says that what Avik Roy
just said is basically false.

14:30.233 --> 14:31.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You will segment the market.

14:31.866 --> 14:34.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You're going to take
healthy people, you're
going to separate them.

14:34.300 --> 14:37.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
You're going to put the
sick people in a market,
and then you're going
to reduce the subsidies

14:37.766 --> 14:42.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you give them to buy insurance,
because the insurance is pegged
at a much skimpier package.

14:44.666 --> 14:49.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is not a recipe for having
people have good insurance
and decreasing deductibles.

14:51.233 --> 14:52.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's actually going to do
the exact reverse of what
the president pledged.

14:52.966 --> 14:54.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do
you want to respond?

14:54.466 --> 14:56.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
AVIK ROY: Absolutely.

14:56.466 --> 14:59.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I would challenge a number
of things that Zeke said
there, as you would expect.

14:59.666 --> 15:03.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The first is that the chief
actuary of the Centers for
Medicare and Medicaid Services,

15:03.866 --> 15:08.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who is an Obama appointee,
published a report a
couple of weeks ago
where he said, in fact,

15:11.366 --> 15:14.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that this bill would bend
down the cost curve and
reduce overall national
health expenditures

15:14.333 --> 15:17.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by making the health care
system more responsive
and more efficient.

15:17.466 --> 15:22.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, actually, the tax credits
in the Senate health care bill
would expand to ensure that

15:24.466 --> 15:26.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
those individuals who are sick,
who need robust coverage would
be able to afford the premiums

15:26.733 --> 15:28.766 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they have.

15:28.766 --> 15:31.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, this bill will actually
provide hundreds of billions,
if not trillions of dollars over

15:31.933 --> 15:34.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the long term to ensure
that those people
can afford coverage.

15:34.200 --> 15:35.200 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

15:35.200 --> 15:37.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
EZEKIEL EMANUEL: It's funny.

15:37.300 --> 15:39.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're talking about giving
more money, when, in fact, the
bill is cutting back the money

15:39.500 --> 15:41.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
it's putting into the
health care system.

15:41.366 --> 15:42.866 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You can't have it both ways.

15:42.866 --> 15:46.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: One final
to you, Dr. Zeke Emanuel.

15:46.033 --> 15:48.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Many parts of the countries,
we know there are going to
be many counties where, under

15:48.633 --> 15:53.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the ACA, the Affordable
Care Act, there's
only one insurer left.

15:53.066 --> 15:54.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Prices have gone up.

15:54.600 --> 15:56.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A lot of people have been
priced out of the market.

15:56.133 --> 15:57.133 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

15:57.133 --> 15:59.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
EZEKIEL EMANUEL: Absolutely.

15:59.200 --> 16:00.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And this is
completely aside from what the
Republicans are trying to do.

16:00.466 --> 16:03.066 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

16:03.066 --> 16:05.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EZEKIEL EMANUEL: Well,
it's not -- no, I would
disagree with there, Judy,
because the uncertainty

16:05.100 --> 16:09.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they have created in the market,
the Republicans - - Marco Rubio
removed the risk corridors

16:09.500 --> 16:12.133 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and the re-insurance proposal.

16:12.133 --> 16:14.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They have also created
uncertainty about whether
they are going to pay the
cost-sharing subsidies.

16:14.633 --> 16:19.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Those are subsidies to families
making less than $70,000
to pay their deductibles.

16:20.733 --> 16:22.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That actually
drives premiums up.

16:22.133 --> 16:24.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There are simple solutions.

16:24.200 --> 16:26.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You put the risk corridors in.

16:26.266 --> 16:29.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You give -- you guarantee
you are going to pay the
cost-sharing subsidies.

16:29.266 --> 16:32.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And you give insurance
companies a tax break.

16:32.200 --> 16:36.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You refund them the tax from
the Affordable Care Act if
they go into counties that have

16:36.766 --> 16:38.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
one or fewer insurances.

16:38.766 --> 16:41.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That will actually stabilize
the insurance markets.

16:41.800 --> 16:45.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And states that run their
insurance exchanges,
like California and
Idaho, they actually are

16:45.800 --> 16:47.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
running pretty well.

16:47.266 --> 16:49.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's the federal side
that's not running so well.

16:49.366 --> 16:52.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the federal side is run
by Mr. Trump's associates.

16:52.000 --> 16:56.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right,
we're going to have to leave it
there, big subject, much to talk

16:56.000 --> 16:57.200 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
about.

16:57.200 --> 16:58.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We are going to continue
to come back to it.

16:58.566 --> 17:00.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Zeke Emanuel, Avik
Roy, we thank you both.

17:00.933 --> 17:02.133 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
DR.

17:02.133 --> 17:06.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
EZEKIEL EMANUEL: Thank
