39:40.266 --> 39:42.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It seems like a slap on the
wrist when you got that kind
of money rolling around.

39:42.933 --> 39:47.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: We repeatedly
reached out to VT Halter,
but they declined to comment

39:47.266 --> 39:49.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
or to be interviewed.

39:49.266 --> 39:54.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're one of seven major
U.S. shipbuilders that contract
with the Navy and Coast Guard.

39:56.066 --> 39:59.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Our review of federal contracts,
court records, and OSHA files
found that, since 2008, the

40:01.066 --> 40:05.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
federal government has awarded
more than $100 billion to these
companies, despite serious

40:06.966 --> 40:11.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
safety lapses that have
endangered and killed workers.

40:11.033 --> 40:16.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In neighboring Mobile, Alabama,
Austal USA is building some
of the country's newest naval

40:17.066 --> 40:19.066 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
vessels.

40:19.066 --> 40:23.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Huge aluminum modules are
assembled into warships on
the banks of the Mobile River.

40:27.000 --> 40:32.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But dozens of its workers have
been injured by a power tool
used to cut through metal.

40:33.433 --> 40:36.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Their own top safety manager
dubbed it the widow maker.

40:36.066 --> 40:40.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARTIN OSBORN, Injured
in Accident: The day
of my accident, I was
using the miller, as

40:40.166 --> 40:41.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it is called at Austal.

40:41.633 --> 40:44.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: Martin
Osborn is a welder at Austal.

40:44.266 --> 40:49.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN OSBORN: I was up in a
boom lift, as we call it, or a
man lift, up in the air about

40:51.266 --> 40:54.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
40 feet, cutting a lifting
lug off the side of a module,
and had a violent kickback.

40:56.966 --> 41:01.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It kicked out of my hands
and went across my left
hand, cutting me pretty bad.

41:03.900 --> 41:07.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I didn't take my glove off,
because, I knew if I did that,
I would have blood everywhere.

41:09.500 --> 41:12.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: Before
Osborn's accident, Austal
modified the Metabo
grinder by replacing

41:13.933 --> 41:17.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the standard disc with
a sawtooth blade made
by an outside company.

41:17.333 --> 41:21.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This made the tool more
versatile, able to cut
through aluminum more quickly.

41:21.800 --> 41:26.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But the manufacturer of
the grinder specifically
warned against using
these blades, saying

41:28.133 --> 41:30.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
they cause frequent kickback
and loss of control.

41:30.333 --> 41:35.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN OSBORN: I have seen
pictures of people getting cut
in their face, in their necks,

41:35.933 --> 41:37.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in their thighs.

41:37.466 --> 41:39.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's the most dangerous tool
I have ever put in my hands.

41:39.533 --> 41:42.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: Does
Austal know that the tool
is as dangerous as it is?

41:42.566 --> 41:45.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MARTIN OSBORN: Yes,
ma'am, they do.

41:45.100 --> 41:48.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: Company
e-mails among Austal's
managers obtained by
Reveal show that, even

41:48.333 --> 41:53.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
before Osborn's accident, they
called the modification lethal,
and the grinders an accident

41:54.400 --> 41:56.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
waiting to happen.

41:56.400 --> 42:00.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Yet, according to Osborn,
Austal workers still
use the grinder daily.

42:00.466 --> 42:04.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MARTIN OSBORN: I have
had numerous supervisors
tell me that, you
know, if you don't want

42:04.766 --> 42:07.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to use the tool, go get
a job at Burger King.

42:07.200 --> 42:11.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: Despite
repeated requests,
Austal declined to
comment for this story.

42:13.766 --> 42:17.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The company has received
more than $6 billion in
Navy contracts since 2008.

42:19.300 --> 42:22.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But when OSHA concluded the saw
exposed workers to amputations,
severe lacerations, and other

42:24.366 --> 42:28.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
injuries, they fined the
shipyard just over $4,000.

42:28.766 --> 42:33.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Austal's own records show at
least 50 workers were injured
by the tool in four years.

42:33.100 --> 42:38.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
BRIAN DUNCAN, Attorney:
Why would any manufacturer
or any company continue
to use a tool after

42:39.466 --> 42:41.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
dozens and dozens of
people have been injured?

42:41.433 --> 42:45.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: Attorney
Brian Duncan is representing
Osborn, along with eight others,

42:45.533 --> 42:49.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
in a lawsuit which he
hopes will bring more
than just compensation.

42:49.200 --> 42:53.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRIAN DUNCAN: I hope, when there
are companies out there that
have intentionally, knowingly

42:53.933 --> 42:58.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
violated safety standards, that
somebody will come in, in that
scenario and will hold those

43:00.500 --> 43:02.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
people accountable.

43:02.433 --> 43:06.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: David
Michaels, the head of OSHA under
former President Obama, was

43:06.033 --> 43:09.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
until recently in charge of
enforcing workplace safety laws.

43:09.966 --> 43:14.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
He acknowledges that
OSHA's maximum penalties
are insufficient,
capped by federal law.

43:16.933 --> 43:18.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID MICHAELS, Former OSHA
Director: They're tiny compared
to the contracts that many of

43:18.866 --> 43:21.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
these companies get
from the government and
from the private sector.

43:21.766 --> 43:26.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: He says
that the real power the
government holds is in
awarding the contracts

43:26.600 --> 43:28.566 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
themselves.

43:28.566 --> 43:30.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID MICHAELS: The biggest
fine is a million dollars,
two million dollars.

43:30.533 --> 43:35.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is petty cash for these
companies that get $100 million,
$200 million, $300 million

43:37.933 --> 43:40.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
contracts from the Defense
Department to build
ships that are protecting
the United States.

43:42.200 --> 43:44.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We need to be protecting
our workers as much as
protecting our shores.

43:44.233 --> 43:46.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MATTHEW PAXTON, President,
Shipbuilders Council of America:
I know Navy puts a high priority

43:46.633 --> 43:50.066 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on safety, as do our shipyards
that are building those ships.

43:50.066 --> 43:54.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: President
of the Shipbuilders
Council of America,
Matthew Paxton, says the

43:54.400 --> 43:57.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
government does consider safety
records when awarding contracts.

43:57.700 --> 44:02.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MATTHEW PAXTON: I think they
take that into a whole lot of
considerations that they have

44:03.800 --> 44:05.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to figure out on
their contracting end.

44:05.300 --> 44:08.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And there's many requirements
that go into that beyond safety.

44:08.466 --> 44:10.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But safety's in there.

44:10.566 --> 44:13.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: Yet,
the Navy's history of
awarding contracts to
companies with repeated

44:13.933 --> 44:18.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
violations suggests that
it places little emphasis
on safety records.

44:20.833 --> 44:24.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NAVSEA, the Naval command
responsible for shipbuilding
contracts, declined an on-camera

44:26.233 --> 44:29.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
interview, but a spokesperson
said in an e-mail that
it's up to OSHA, not
the Navy, to enforce

44:30.200 --> 44:32.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
federal safety laws.

44:32.366 --> 44:36.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They added: "We are not
the overlords of private
shipyards when it comes
to workplace safety."

44:38.066 --> 44:40.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
DAVID MICHAELS: The
Navy has the power.

44:40.066 --> 44:44.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They can easily say, if
workers are hurt, if you don't
follow the basic commonsense

44:45.400 --> 44:48.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
safety rules, you don't
get any more contracts.

44:48.166 --> 44:50.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That would have a huge impact.

44:50.233 --> 44:54.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: Former
President Obama signed
an executive order
that required companies

44:54.500 --> 44:59.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to disclose three years of
safety violations when vying
for large federal contracts.

45:00.766 --> 45:03.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But a federal court
blocked that order.

45:03.400 --> 45:08.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, this spring, Congress
drafted a resolution to
overturn it altogether.

45:08.133 --> 45:10.033 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

45:10.033 --> 45:12.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MITCH MCCONNELL (R-KY),
Majority Leader: The regulations
aren't issued in a vacuum.

45:12.400 --> 45:17.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They have real economic
consequences that can
harm the middle class.

45:19.366 --> 45:22.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They can kill jobs, raise
prices, depress wages
and lower opportunities.

45:24.700 --> 45:28.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: President
Trump signed the resolution into
law, meaning companies don't

45:28.333 --> 45:33.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
have to disclose their
safety records when
competing for contracts.

45:35.300 --> 45:38.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
That same month, Senator
Elizabeth Warren asked
the Justice Department
to open a criminal

45:39.566 --> 45:40.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
investigation into VT Halter.

45:40.733 --> 45:42.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

45:42.800 --> 45:45.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ELIZABETH WARREN (D),
Massachusetts: We want
to get to the bottom
of why people have died

45:45.366 --> 45:49.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and what kind of responsibility
the company itself has.

45:49.133 --> 45:53.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: Warren wants
the Navy to scrutinize safety
records when granting contracts

45:53.933 --> 45:54.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to all shipbuilders.

45:54.933 --> 45:56.966 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

45:56.966 --> 45:59.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ELIZABETH WARREN: And in the
same way that they look at
how much is it going to cost,

45:59.533 --> 46:04.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they also need to look
at whether or not this is
a contractor who injures
and kills employees.

46:06.533 --> 46:10.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: At Austal's
shipyard, Martin Osborn still
frequently uses a sawtooth blade

46:13.100 --> 46:15.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
like the one that
cost him his finger.

46:15.633 --> 46:20.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says nothing will change
unless shipyards are made to
pay a price for putting workers

46:21.433 --> 46:23.466 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
at risk.

46:23.466 --> 46:26.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARTIN OSBORN: We're not
worried about if you get cut
or the next guy gets cut.

46:26.533 --> 46:29.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We just put another guy in your
place and move on down the road.

46:29.033 --> 46:34.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AUBREY ADEN-BUIE: For the
"PBS NewsHour," I'm Aubrey
Aden-Buie in Mobile, Alabama.

46:39.833 --> 46:44.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally,
remembering filmmaker
George Romero, the master
of the zombie movie

46:54.733 --> 46:59.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and a man whose influence
in the business went further
than many moviegoers realize.

47:00.666 --> 47:02.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has our look.

47:02.700 --> 47:06.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ACTOR: Medical examination of
victims bodies show conclusively
that the killers are eating

47:10.800 --> 47:12.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the flesh of the
people they kill.

47:12.866 --> 47:16.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: With a $100,000
in 1968, George Romero brought
the undead back to life in

47:16.133 --> 47:18.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
American culture.

47:18.233 --> 47:22.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
His "Night of the Living
Dead" became a cult
classic, and launched a
modern zombie industry

47:24.533 --> 47:27.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of soulless ghouls with
a taste for human flesh
popping up everywhere today.

47:29.833 --> 47:32.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For Romero, his films were
about more than just blood
and graphic violence.

47:32.233 --> 47:35.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GEORGE ROMERO, Director:
This series of films have
been sort of my platform.

47:35.933 --> 47:39.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's ripe for metaphor.

47:39.333 --> 47:44.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the zombies, to me, have
always represented the people
that are just unwilling to stand

47:47.866 --> 47:49.333 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
up.

47:49.333 --> 47:52.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, you know, there are a
lot of living dead in America.

47:52.266 --> 47:57.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: "Night of the
Living Dead," starring an
African-American actor, was seen

47:57.233 --> 48:02.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as a kind of social
commentary on racism and the
paranoid mood of its time.

48:04.266 --> 48:07.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
A decade later, Romero's
first sequel, "Dawn of
the Dead," played on
the excesses of American

48:09.433 --> 48:11.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
consumerism.

48:11.400 --> 48:15.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Roger Ebert dubbed it one of
the best horror films ever
made, savagely merciless in its

48:16.100 --> 48:19.133 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
satiric view.

48:19.133 --> 48:23.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Romero followed up with many
other films, including four
more in the "Dead" series,

48:23.900 --> 48:26.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with varying degrees
of box office success.

48:26.400 --> 48:31.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the zombie world he
unleashed took on a massive
multibillion-dollar life of its

48:33.433 --> 48:36.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
own in blockbuster films like
"World War Z," video games,
and AMC's "The Walking Dead."

48:39.300 --> 48:44.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That, in turn, led Romero
to sour a bit on the genre
he helped popularize.

48:45.033 --> 48:47.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He spoke on NPR in 2014.

48:47.133 --> 48:50.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GEORGE ROMERO: It's, all of
a sudden, you can't make a
little zombie film anymore.

48:50.833 --> 48:53.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Has to be special
effects and big budget.

48:53.200 --> 48:55.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And I'm not -- I'm just
not interested in that.

48:55.600 --> 48:59.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Later in life,
he shifted to different media,
including teaming up with

48:59.733 --> 49:02.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Marvel to publish a
comic book series.

49:02.400 --> 49:06.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
George Romero died Sunday
in Toronto from lung cancer.

49:06.233 --> 49:10.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
He was 77 years old.

49:10.933 --> 49:15.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And for more on George Romero
and his impact, I'm joined by
Justin Chang, film critic for

49:15.733 --> 49:17.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The Los Angeles Times.

49:17.200 --> 49:18.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome to you, Justin.

49:18.833 --> 49:20.966 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Zombies, who would have thought?

49:20.966 --> 49:24.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What explains the impact
of those early films?

49:24.133 --> 49:27.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUSTIN CHANG, The Los Angeles
Times: Well, I think when you
have a film like "Night of

49:27.933 --> 49:32.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Living Dead," which is, I
think, one of the great debut
films that any director in

49:34.966 --> 49:38.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
or outside the horror genre
has ever given us, you have to
look at the context, you know,

49:40.566 --> 49:43.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Vietnam, Martin Luther
King Jr.'s assassination,
the recent assassinations
of the Kennedy brothers.

49:44.800 --> 49:46.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was a time of, obviously,
great social unrest.

49:46.933 --> 49:51.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And George Romero found,
unwittingly or not, a perfect
metaphor for that unrest.

49:53.800 --> 49:58.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think it was about the
primitiveness of the filmmaking,
the very raw technique.

50:00.966 --> 50:04.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was shot on a $114,000
budget, which is about
$800,000 today, still
a very small budget.

50:06.066 --> 50:10.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And he achieved this kind
of -- a film that was almost
like a documentary nightmare.

50:12.866 --> 50:16.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And it really captured,
I think, a sense of rage
and of pointlessness,
a kind of senseless,

50:18.500 --> 50:22.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
arbitrary killing that
was really unsettling for
audiences at the time,
and is still enormously

50:23.433 --> 50:25.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
unsettling today.

50:25.433 --> 50:29.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: His films, of
course, largely done on the
cheap, but somehow a cult thing

50:29.100 --> 50:32.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
grew into a very large
cultural phenomenon.

50:32.666 --> 50:37.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He wasn't so crazy -- as
we heard, he wasn't so
crazy about what followed?

50:37.166 --> 50:39.133 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUSTIN CHANG: Absolutely.

50:39.133 --> 50:43.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, we live in a culture
where zombies are proliferating
on screens, whether it's

50:45.400 --> 50:48.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"World War Z" or "The Walking
Dead," which is still hugely
popular, or the remake of

50:50.900 --> 50:54.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
"Dawn of the Dead" about 13
years ago, and terrific spoofs
like "Shaun of the Dead,"

50:54.566 --> 50:58.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which I think is one of the
few that George Romero has
professed to actually liking.

50:58.766 --> 51:03.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, in a way, he was, I think,
understandably disenchanted with
the way that Hollywood really

51:07.000 --> 51:12.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
mainstreamed the zombie film and
the zombie TV show, and in some
ways took out that edginess,

51:14.566 --> 51:18.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that political subtext that he
was so good at putting in there.

51:18.233 --> 51:22.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think he especially
resented things like
"The Walking Dead,"
because it made it

51:22.533 --> 51:27.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very difficult for him to get
his own zombie movies financed
on an independent level.

51:29.500 --> 51:33.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And he was a consummate
independent filmmaker,
and something of a
Hollywood outsider and

51:34.866 --> 51:37.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
skeptic, I think, all his
career, which makes his success
all the more remarkable.

51:37.933 --> 51:42.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: For a lot of
people, this stuff goes way too
far, right, the graphic violence

51:45.033 --> 51:48.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's part of our society
and that's really part of
our entertainment culture.

51:48.200 --> 51:51.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Did he help create that,
for better or for worse?

51:51.633 --> 51:55.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUSTIN CHANG: I don't think
it's entirely fair to lay that
as George Romero's doorstep.

51:55.500 --> 52:00.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I say that as someone who's
on the more squeamish side of
the spectrum as far as horror

52:01.266 --> 52:03.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
movie viewers goes.

52:03.300 --> 52:06.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I think you have to look
at his films, a film like
"Dawn of the Dead," which is,

52:06.133 --> 52:08.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I think, as great a
masterpiece as "Night
of the Living Dead" is.

52:08.966 --> 52:11.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There is always something more
going on beneath the violence.

52:11.400 --> 52:15.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you're just there
for the splatter and the
viscera, you will get that.

52:15.400 --> 52:19.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But he gives you -- he's
always asking you to look a
little closer, see what's going

52:19.800 --> 52:23.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on, see who these zombies
represent, see who the
real monsters are in a way.

52:23.500 --> 52:28.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I don't think
it's entirely fair to
say that he's responsible
for the fetishization

52:29.633 --> 52:31.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
and exploitation of
violence in our culture.

52:31.700 --> 52:35.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He's using it -- I mean, he's
exploiting violence in his own
way, to very brilliant and very

52:35.900 --> 52:37.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
provocative ends.

52:37.933 --> 52:40.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Just briefly, I
do want to mention the passing
of another movie figure,

52:40.833 --> 52:43.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the actor Martin Landau.

52:43.366 --> 52:47.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He was known early on, on
television, in "Mission:
Impossible," later in
films, including "Ed

52:48.900 --> 52:51.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Wood," for which he won an
Oscar for best supporting actor.

52:51.033 --> 52:56.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let's take a look at a short
scene from Woody Allen's 1989
film "Crimes and Misdemeanors."

52:57.533 --> 52:59.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARTIN LANDAU, Actor: This
is what you plan on doing.

52:59.600 --> 53:02.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're going to hold on
to me with threats, right,
stupid threats and slander?

53:02.800 --> 53:04.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
This is your idea
of love, right?

53:04.033 --> 53:05.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ACTRESS: I will
not be tossed out.

53:05.333 --> 53:06.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I want to speak to Miriam.

53:06.500 --> 53:08.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARTIN LANDAU: Think.

53:08.166 --> 53:11.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
For Christ's sake, think
what the hell you are
doing to me, will you?

53:11.433 --> 53:12.933 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Please.

53:12.933 --> 53:15.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Justin Chang, a
brief thought on Martin Landau?

53:15.033 --> 53:18.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUSTIN CHANG: Martin Landau
was such a wonderful actor.

53:18.633 --> 53:23.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that scene you play sort of,
I think, captures his elegance
and gravitas, his ability

53:24.733 --> 53:28.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to play a silken villain
that we feel for.

53:28.433 --> 53:33.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In that film, he's an adulterous
husband who contemplates
the murder of his lover.

53:35.333 --> 53:39.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's -- you know, I'm
reminded, too, of his great
performance many decades earlier

53:41.833 --> 53:44.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Alfred Hitchcock's "North
By Northwest," where he took
the role of a villain's number

53:44.900 --> 53:49.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
two and made it something
really memorable and really
incisive out of that.

53:51.900 --> 53:55.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so it's not that he could
only play villains, certainly
not, but he had, I think, a real

53:55.533 --> 54:00.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
talent for playing morally
ambiguous characters,
and doing it superbly.

54:00.133 --> 54:03.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right,
Justin Chang of The Los Angeles
Times, thank you very much.

